  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Peche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: unexplained.","German: possibly a variant of   Pech   ‘pitch, tar’.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Peče</b> or of its Germanized form   Petsche  , which is also a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Pech","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Jose, Manuel, Alvaro, Diego, Edelmira, Emilio, Francisco, Gilberto, Jorge, Jose Angel.  German Gerhard, Hans, Ilse, Lutz, Manfred, Wolf.","Czech and Slovak; Sorbian (<b>Pěch</b> and <b>P'ech</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Petr</i> (Czech), <i>Pětš</i> (Lower Sorbian), and   Peter   (Slovak). This is also a Germanized form of the Upper Sorbian cognate <b>Pjech</b>.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>pech</i> (German <i>Pech</i>) ‘pitch, tar’, presumably a nickname for someone with exceptionally dark skin or hair, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who prepared, sold, or used pitch. This may in part also be the origin of a homonymic Polish, Czech, and Slovak surname (compare above and below)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William de Peche was born about 1352, in Suffolk, England, his father, Simon de Pechey, was 32 and his mother, Agnes Holme, was 24. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Eleanor de Canc. He died on 6 February 1375, in Dorset, England, at the age of 24."},"et":{"about 1352–6 February 1375":"umbes 1352–6. veebruar 1375","1352–1375":"1352–1375","1355–1400":"1355–1400","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1355–1386":"1355–1386","1322–1398":"1322–1398","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1322":"1322","1398":"1398","1386":"1386","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","6 February 1375":"6. veebruar 1375","about 1352":"umbes 1352","1329":"1329","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"fi":{"about 1352–6 February 1375":"noin 1352–6. helmikuuta 1375","1352–1375":"1352–1375","1355–1400":"1355–1400","1335–Female":"1335–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1355–1386":"1355–1386","1322–1398":"1322–1398","1329–Female":"1329–Kuollut","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1322":"1322","1398":"1398","1386":"1386","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","6 February 1375":"6. helmikuuta 1375","about 1352":"noin 1352","1329":"1329","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"fr":{"about 1352–6 February 1375":"environ 1352–6 février 1375","1352–1375":"1352–1375","1355–1400":"1355–1400","1335–Female":"1335–Décédée","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1355–1386":"1355–1386","1322–1398":"1322–1398","1329–Female":"1329–Décédée","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1322":"1322","1398":"1398","1386":"1386","1375":"1375","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","6 February 1375":"6 février 1375","abo